There lived in San Francisco at this time, i.e.
1909, a Chinese lad fired with a determination to fly,
and though he read with no little apprehension of
Henri Farman's financial failure on Long Island, his
ambition was none the less diminished. This boy, a
youth of twenty years, was employed on the staff of THE
WORLD, San Francisco's leading contemporary Chinese
dailyâ€¢
In 1914, at Canton and other South China cities,
an old Curtiss "Pusher" biplane flown by the illustrious
"Art" Lym, aroused nation-wide interest. He, the
Chinese lad late of San Francisco, had realized his am-
bition to fly, then embarked for China, together with a
youthful understudy named Chan Pon, two second-hand
planes, and an abundance of enthusiasm. He speedily set
about injecting the latter possession into the more ven-
turesome of his countrymen. Lym failed to find flying a
profitable undertaking in the beginning, however, as
those bold enough to desire instruction seldom possessed
the means with which to pay for it. He experienced a
serious setback shortly after his arrival in China when
he wrecked one of the two planes and sustained a broken
leg while making an exhibition flight at Swatow.
Never-
theless, success finally arrived, and his future as an
airman was established in China.
